212. J Aging Soc Policy. 2002;14(1):35-52. doi: 10.1300/J031v14n01_04.

Is Swedish pension reform the right medicine for aging Europe?

Palmer E(1).

Author information:
(1)Uppsala University, Sweden. edward.palmer@abc.se

Following the Second World War, the idea of the life course with distinct 
periods of education, work, and retirement became popular as a result of the 
alliance of interests of unions and management, with politicians seizing the 
opportunity to accommodate them. These "social partners" implemented benefit 
rules and created practices for using old age and disability to ease the exit of 
older workers. Although justifiable at the time, now those rules and practices 
hinder individual and employer incentives to invest in human capital and work 
environments that enable older workers to remain in the workforce. The article 
argues that the workforce environment of the coming half-century, which is 
relevant for persons born around 2000, is much different from that a hundred 
years earlier, which determined the opportunities for people born around 1900. 
People are healthier and live much longer and work environments are friendlier. 
The article argues that it is no longer justifiable to subsidize exit from the 
workforce around the age of 60 for healthy workers, especially in view of the 
coming labor shortage in Europe. It also argues that the introduction of the 
principles of the Swedish NDC pension reform in Europe would provide 
possibilities for flexible exit from the workforce and remove impediments to 
labor mobility in Europe, which are embedded in many of Europe's present pension 
arrangements.

DOI: 10.1300/J031v14n01_04
PMID: 12503328 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


213. J Aging Soc Policy. 2002;14(1):81-93. doi: 10.1300/J031v14n01_07.

Social security reform ideas in Japan.

Watanabe N(1).

Author information:
(1)Rissoyo University, Japan. watanab8@ris.ac.jp

Japan has a complex social security system. This article discusses the 
demographic and economic situation in Japan as background for understanding the 
setting in which the social security system functions. Japan has a three-pillar 
system for retirement income. The first pillar is the social security pension 
plan; the second pillar is the voluntary occupational pension plan; and the 
third pillar is personal savings, including the personal pension plan. The most 
important part of the retirement income system is the social security pension 
plan, which paid benefits accounting for 64% of the total income of elderly 
households in 1998. The five Employees' Pension Plans are established on a 
compulsory social insurance basis. Most large Japanese employers have a 
mandatory retirement age. Over 90% of all employees, including public sector 
ones, must retire from their career jobs at age 60.

